         <h3>
            1. What is fusion power?
         </h3>
         <div class="content">
            <p>
               Fusion power promises to produce large amounts of energy at low cost from practically unlimited fuel, with little or no pollution, and to satisfy mankind's energy demands for the
               foreseeable future.
            </p>
            <p>
               Fusion is any nuclear reaction in which two light nuclei combine to form a heavier nucleus with the release of energy via Einstein's famous equivalence of mass and energy E = mc
               <sup>2</sup>. Nuclear fusion powers the sun and other stars.
            </p>
            <p>
               Despite enormous progress in our scientific understanding of fusion, practical power production remains elusive.
            </p>
         </div><a name="question2" id="question2"> </a>
         <h3>
            2. Why is fusion needed when there are plenty of alternative energy sources?
         </h3>
         <div class="content">
            <p>
               Controlled fusion power on earth would constitute an environmentally friendly, economically competitive and effectively limitless source of energy.
            </p>
            <p>
               By the turn of the next century, the Earth's population is predicted to reach 12 billion. This unprecedented increase in population, coupled with rising prosperity in the developing
               world will place huge demands on global energy supplies.
            </p>
            <p>
               Fossil fuels, currently our primary source of energy, are beginning to run out, and burning them releases greenhouse gases which is leading to climate change that if unchecked will
               impose unacceptable economic and humanitarian costs on the global population within a generation.
            </p>
            <p>
               Conventional nuclear power (fission) produces long-lived and very hazardous radioactive waste, and the waste material can be used to build nuclear weapons. Furthermore, fuel for
               fission reactors is limited.
            </p>
            <p>
               Renewable energy sources such as wind, wave or solar power provide variable output and are unlikely to ever satisfy total demand. At current costs they are nearly always economically
               uncompetitive with fossil fuels.
            </p>
         </div>
