         <h3>
            3. Is fusion safe, and how does it differ to fission?
         </h3>
         <div class="content">
            <p>
               Both fusion and fission are forms of nuclear energy, but are fundamentally different: fusion is the combination of light nuclei, and fission is the splitting of heavy nuclei.
            </p>
            <p>
               From a safety point of view, with fusion there is absolutely no chance of a runaway reaction like the reaction that destroyed the Chernobyl fission reactor.
            </p>
            <p>
               Fusion requires the active maintenance of plasmas (ionized gases) at extraordinarily high temperatures and pressures, and any departure from these conditions will result in a rapid
               cooling of the reacting plasma and the termination of the reaction. Thus if a fusion reactor malfunctions it will shut down automatically, unlike a fission reactor that can continue to
               operate dangerously after the reactor malfunctions.
            </p>
            <p>
               The fuel for fusion reactions is hydrogen and other light elements that are abundant in seawater and throughout the earth's crust. The fusion of all of the deuterium, a form of
               hydrogen, in the sea could easily meet the expected global energy demand beyond the expected lifetime of the planet. If this demand is met with uranium, the fuel for fission reactors,
               it will be exhausted within twenty to fifty years.
            </p>
            <p>
               The waste from fusion is likely to consist only of small amounts of helium, a completely harmless and in fact useful gas, which can be released into the atmosphere. Waste from fission
               reactors has to be disposed of in securely guarded repositories deep underground, and remains hazardous for tens of thousands of years.
            </p>
         </div><a name="question4" id="question4"> </a>
         <h3>
            4. What are we proposing?
         </h3>
         <div class="content">
            <p>
               We have a patent for a nuclear fusion reactor based on a design that was the first to demonstrate fusion power production in 1967.
            </p>
            <p>
               This approach, called inertial electrostatic confinement, or IEC, has been abandoned by the mainstream community due to early disappointments in its development and the ostensibly
               greater promise of alternative approaches. We have designed a modification that we believe will solve the problems with the IEC approach.
            </p>
            <p>
               We aim to build a prototype machine that demonstrates net power production within three years of obtaining funding.
            </p>
         </div><a name="question5" id="question5"> </a>
