         <h3>
            6. What is the state of fusion power development today?
         </h3>
         <div class="content">
            <p>
               The accepted consensus in policy and scientific circles is that commercially available fusion power is at least thirty years away.
            </p>
            <p>
               The US fusion budget stands at approximately $250m annually, and the world budget is about ten times as large. The vast majority of this money is being funneled into an international
               mega-project, the construction of a very large tokamak in the South of France called ITER (International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor. ITER is designed to demonstrate a small net
               energy release within a twenty-year lifetime, and will then be followed by a larger prototype reactor with the aim of producing usable power.
            </p>
            <p>
               The tokamak is a design for a fusion reactor that has been the front-runner in the mainstream fusion community since the 1970s. Tokamaks are large, donut shaped reactors that aim to
               confine hot plasmas using strong magnetic fields. They are necessarily large, complex and expensive.
            </p>
            <p>
               Aside from the tokamak, there are many other design concepts for fusion reactors which have been neglected, abandoned, or even forgotten by the scientific community due to early
               dominance of tokamak-based programs and subsequent funding squeezes.
            </p>
         </div><a name="question7" id="question7"> </a>
         <h3>
            7. Why is IEC better?
         </h3>
         <div class="content">
            <p>
               IEC promises a cheap, simple approach to commercial fusion power generation that could be developed much, much faster on a modest budget, as compared with a complex, expensive
               multinational project such as ITER.
            </p>
            <p>
               IEC has the additional advantage of being able to use so-called advanced fuels that produce no radiation. The physics of most other fusion reactor designs prevent them from using
               advanced fuels, and other designs are therefore burdened with the necessity of managing large amounts of radiation.
            </p>
         </div>
         <p>
            Despite the merits of IEC, the mainstream magnetic fusion community rejects IEC as unlikely to lead to the development of commercial fusion reactors.
         </p><a name="question8" id="question8"> </a>
         <h3>
            8. If IEC is so promising why is it not being widely used?
         </h3>
         <div class="content">
            <p>
               Many fusion researchers have never heard of IEC, and most fusion scientists have made their careers in tokamak-related projects.
            </p>
            <p>
               Controversy surrounds the viability of IEC devices. Work published in the last decade apparently calculated that traditional IEC machines could never produce net power. More recent
               work, however, robustly refutes the earlier calculations; in any case no published work exists that takes account of the improvements that we are proposing.
            </p>
